# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: igbt-power
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] An **insulated-gate bipolar transistor** (**IGBT**) is a three-terminal power semiconductor device primarily forming an electronic switch.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] It was developed to combine high efficiency with fast switching.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] It consists of four alternating layers (NPNP) that are controlled by a metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) gate structure.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Although the structure of the IGBT is topologically similar to a thyristor with a "MOS" gate (MOS-gate thyristor), the thyristor action is completely suppressed, and only the transistor action is permitted in the entire device operation range.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Since it is designed to turn on and off rapidly, the IGBT can synthesize complex waveforms with pulse-width modulation and low-pass filters, thus it is also used in switching amplifiers in sound systems and industrial control systems.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] In switching applications, modern devices feature pulse repetition rates well into the ultrasonic-range frequencies, which are at least ten times higher than audio frequencies handled by the device when used as an analog audio amplifier.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] As of 2010, the IGBT was the second most widely used power transistor, after the power MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] An IGBT cell is constructed similarly to an n-channel vertical-construction power MOSFET, except the n+ drain is replaced with a p+ collector layer, thus forming a vertical PNP bipolar junction transistor.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This additional p+ region creates a cascade connection of a PNP bipolar junction transistor with the surface n-channel MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The whole structure comprises a four-layered NPNP.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The bipolar point-contact transistor was invented in December 1947 at the Bell Telephone Laboratories by John Bardeen and Walter Brattain under the direction of William Shockley.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The junction version, known as the bipolar junction transistor (BJT), was invented by Shockley in 1948.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Later a similar thyristor was proposed by William Shockley in 1950 and developed in 1956 by power engineers at General Electric (GE).
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) was later invented at Bell Labs between 1959 and 1960.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The basic IGBT mode of operation, where a pnp transistor is driven by a MOSFET, was first proposed by K.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Akagiri of Mitsubishi Electric in the Japanese patent S47-21739, which was filed in 1968.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Scharf patented a NPNP transistor device combining MOS and bipolar capabilities for power control and switching.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The development of the IGBT was characterised by an effort to completely suppress the thyristor operation, or the latch-up, in the four-layer device because the latch-up caused fatal device self-destruction.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] IGBTs had thus been established when the complete suppression of the latch-up of the parasitic thyristor was achieved.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Wheatley developed a similar device claiming non-latch-up.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] They patented the device in 1980, referring to it as "power MOSFET with an anode region" for which "no thyristor action occurs under any device operating conditions".
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Nakagawa et al. invented the device design concept of non-latch-up IGBTs in 1984.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The invention is characterised by the device design setting the device saturation current below the latch-up current, which triggers the parasitic thyristor.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This invention achieved complete suppression of the parasitic thyristor action for the first time, because the maximal collector current was limited by the saturation current and never exceeded the latch-up current.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] In the early development stage of the IGBT, research was aimed at increasing the latch-up current itself to suppress the latch-up of the parasitic thyristor.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] However, all these efforts failed because the IGBT could conduct an enormously large current.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Successful suppression of latch-up became possible by constraining the maximal collector current to stay below the latch-up current, by controlling or reducing the saturation current of the inherent MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This was the breakthrough behind the non-latch-up IGBT, which in turn made "Becke’s device" possible.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT is characterised by its ability to simultaneously handle a high voltage and a large current.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The product of the voltage and the current density that the IGBT can handle reached more than 5×105 W/cm2, which far exceeded the value, 2×105 W/cm2, of existing power devices such as bipolar transistors and power MOSFETs.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This is a consequence of the large safe operating area of the IGBT.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT is the most rugged and the strongest power device yet developed, affording ease of use and so displacing bipolar transistors and even gate turn-off thyristors (GTOs).
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This excellent feature of the IGBT had suddenly emerged when the non-latch-up IGBT was established in 1984 by solving the problem of so-called "latch-up", which is the main cause of device destruction or device failure.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Before that, the developed devices were very weak and were easily destroyed by "latch-up".
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Practical devices capable of operating over an extended current range were first reported by B.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The first experimental demonstration of a practical discrete vertical IGBT device was reported by Baliga at the IEEE International Electron Devices Meeting (IEDM) that year.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] General Electric commercialized Baliga's IGBT device the same year.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Baliga was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame for the invention of the IGBT.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] A similar paper was also submitted by J.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Russel et al. to IEEE Electron Device Letter in 1982.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The applications for the device were initially regarded by the power electronics community to be severely restricted by its slow switching speed and latch-up of the parasitic thyristor structure inherent within the device.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] However, it was demonstrated by Baliga and also by A.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Goodman et al. in 1983 that the switching speed could be adjusted over a broad range by using electron irradiation.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This was followed by demonstration of operation of the device at elevated temperatures by Baliga in 1985.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Successful efforts to suppress the latch-up of the parasitic thyristor and the scaling of the voltage rating of the devices at GE allowed the introduction of commercial devices in 1983, which could be used for a wide variety of applications.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The electrical characteristics of GE's device, IGT D94FQ/FR4, were reported in detail by Marvin W.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Smith in the proceedings of PCI April 1984.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] 12 of the proceedings that turn-off above 10 amperes for gate resistance of 5 kΩ and above 5 amperes for gate resistance of 1 kΩ was limited by switching safe operating area although IGT D94FQ/FR4 was able to conduct 40 amperes of collector current.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Smith also stated that the switching safe operating area was limited by the latch-up of the parasitic thyristor.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Complete suppression of the parasitic thyristor action and the resultant non-latch-up IGBT operation for the entire device operation range was achieved by A.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The non-latch-up design concept was filed for US patents.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] To test the lack of latch-up, the prototype 1200 V IGBTs were directly connected without any loads across a 600 V constant-voltage source and were switched on for 25 microseconds.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The entire 600 V was dropped across the device, and a large short-circuit current flowed.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The devices successfully withstood this severe condition.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This was the first demonstration of so-called "short-circuit-withstanding-capability" in IGBTs.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Non-latch-up IGBT operation was ensured, for the first time, for the entire device operation range.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] In this sense, the non-latch-up IGBT proposed by Hans W.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Products of non-latch-up IGBTs were first commercialized by Toshiba in 1985.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This was the real birth of the present IGBT.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Once the non-latch-up capability was achieved in IGBTs, it was found that IGBTs exhibited very rugged and a very large safe operating area.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] It was demonstrated that the product of the operating current density and the collector voltage exceeded the theoretical limit of bipolar transistors, 2×105 W/cm2 and reached 5×105 W/cm2.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The insulating material is typically made of solid polymers, which have issues with degradation.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] There are developments that use an ion gel to improve manufacturing and reduce the voltage required.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Second-generation devices were much improved.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The current third-generation IGBTs are even better, with speed rivaling power MOSFETs and excellent ruggedness and tolerance of overloads.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Extremely high pulse ratings of second- and third-generation devices also make them useful for generating large power pulses in areas including particle and plasma physics, where they are starting to supersede older devices such as thyratrons and triggered spark gaps.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] High pulse ratings and low prices on the surplus market also make them attractive to the high-voltage hobbyists for controlling large amounts of power to drive devices such as solid-state Tesla coils and coilguns.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] As of 2010, the IGBT is the second most widely used power transistor, after the power MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT accounts for 27% of the power transistor market, second only to the power MOSFET (53%), and ahead of the RF amplifier (11%) and bipolar junction transistor (9%).
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT is widely used in consumer electronics, industrial technology, the energy sector, aerospace electronic devices, and transportation.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT combines the simple gate-drive characteristics of power MOSFETs with the high-current and low-saturation-voltage capability of bipolar transistors.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT combines an isolated-gate FET for the control input and a bipolar power transistor as a switch in a single device.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The IGBT is used in medium- to high-power applications like switched-mode power supplies, traction motor control and induction heating.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Large IGBT modules typically consist of many devices in parallel and can have very high current-handling capabilities in the order of hundreds of amperes with blocking voltages of 6500 V.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] These IGBTs can control loads of hundreds of kilowatts.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] An IGBT features a significantly lower forward voltage drop compared to a conventional MOSFET in higher blocking voltage rated devices, although MOSFETS exhibit much lower forward voltage at lower current densities due to the absence of a diode Vf in the IGBT's output BJT.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] As the blocking voltage rating of both MOSFET and IGBT devices increases, the depth of the n- drift region must increase and the doping must decrease, resulting in roughly square relationship decrease in forward conduction versus blocking voltage capability of the device.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] By injecting minority carriers (holes) from the collector p+ region into the n- drift region during forward conduction, the resistance of the n- drift region is considerably reduced.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] In general, high voltage, high current and lower frequencies favor the IGBT while low voltage, medium current and high switching frequencies are the domain of the MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Circuits with IGBTs can be developed and modeled with various circuit simulating computer programs such as SPICE, Saber, and other programs.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] To simulate an IGBT circuit, the device (and other devices in the circuit) must have a model which predicts or simulates the device's response to various voltages and currents on their electrical terminals.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] For more precise simulations the effect of temperature on various parts of the IGBT may be included with the simulation.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Two common methods of modeling are available: device physics-based model, equivalent circuits or macromodels.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] SPICE simulates IGBTs using a macromodel that combines an ensemble of components like FETs and BJTs in a Darlington configuration.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] An alternative physics-based model is the Hefner model, introduced by Allen Hefner of the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Hefner's model is fairly complex but has shown good results.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Hefner's model is described in a 1988 paper and was later extended to a thermo-electrical model which includes the IGBT's response to internal heating.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] This model has been added to a version of the Saber simulation software.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The failure mechanisms of IGBTs includes overstress (O) and wearout (wo) separately.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The wearout failures mainly include bias temperature instability (BTI), hot carrier injection (HCI), time-dependent dielectric breakdown (TDDB), electromigration (ECM), solder fatigue, material reconstruction, corrosion.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] The overstress failures mainly include electrostatic discharge (ESD), latch-up, avalanche, secondary breakdown, wire-bond liftoff and burnout.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Failure assessment of IGBTs is becoming a topic of interest for predictive maintenance in several applications where IGBTs are widely used such as transportation, telecommunication, and computers.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] It is particularly challenging given the difficult nature of the problem from a physical and a statistical point of view.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Physics of failure are yet to be proven to generalize well to IGBTs, whereas data-driven models require high-quality data of IGBT failures that is often costly to obtain.
[src:igbt-power/insulated-gate-bipolar-transistor] Given these challenges, most state-of-the-art failure assessment models utilise hybrid approaches which combine physics-of-failure and data-driven models.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A **power semiconductor device** is a semiconductor device used as a switch or rectifier in power electronics (for example in a switched-mode power supply).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Such a device is also called a **power device** or, when used in an integrated circuit, a **power IC**.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A power semiconductor device is usually used in "commutation mode" (i.e., it is either on or off), and therefore has a design optimized for such usage; it should usually not be used in linear operation.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Linear power circuits are widespread as voltage regulators, audio amplifiers, and radio frequency amplifiers.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Power semiconductors are found in systems delivering as little as a few tens of milliwatts for a headphone amplifier, up to around a gigawatt in a high-voltage direct current transmission line.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The first electronic device used in power circuits was the electrolytic rectifier – an early version was described by a French experimenter, A.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] These were briefly popular with early radio experimenters as they could be improvised from aluminum sheets, and household chemicals.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] They had low withstand voltages and limited efficiency.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The first solid-state power semiconductor devices were copper oxide rectifiers, used in early battery chargers and power supplies for radio equipment, announced in 1927 by L.O.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The first germanium power semiconductor device appeared in 1952 with the introduction of the power diode by R.N.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] It had a reverse voltage blocking capability of 200 V and a current rating of 35 A.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Germanium bipolar transistors with substantial power handling capabilities (100 mA collector current) were introduced around 1952; with essentially the same construction as signal devices, but better heat sinking.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Power handling capability evolved rapidly, and by 1954 germanium alloy junction transistors with 100 watt dissipation were available.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] These were all relatively low-frequency devices, used up to around 100 kHz, and up to 85 degrees Celsius junction temperature.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Silicon power transistors were not made until 1957, but when available had better frequency response than germanium devices, and could operate up to 150 C junction temperature.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] It is able to withstand very high reverse breakdown voltage and is also capable of carrying high current.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] However, one disadvantage of the thyristor in switching circuits is that once it becomes 'latched-on' in the conducting state; it cannot be turned off by external control, as the thyristor turn-off is passive, i.e., the power must be disconnected from the device.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Thyristors which could be turned off, called gate turn-off thyristors (GTO), were introduced in 1960.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] These overcome some limitations of the ordinary thyristor, because they can be turned on or off with an applied signal.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The MOSFET was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960 Generations of MOSFET transistors enabled power designers to achieve performance and density levels not possible with bipolar transistors.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Due to improvements in MOSFET technology (initially used to produce integrated circuits), the power MOSFET became available in the 1970s.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] In 1969, Hitachi introduced the first vertical power MOSFET, which would later be known as the VMOS (V-groove MOSFET).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] From 1974, Yamaha, JVC, Pioneer Corporation, Sony and Toshiba began manufacturing audio amplifiers with power MOSFETs.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] International Rectifier introduced a 25 A, 400 V power MOSFET in 1978.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] This device allows operation at higher frequencies than a bipolar transistor, but is limited to low-voltage applications.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The insulated-gate bipolar transistor (IGBT) was developed in the 1980s, and became widely available in the 1990s.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] This component has the power handling capability of the bipolar transistor and the advantages of the isolated gate drive of the power MOSFET.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Some common power devices are the power MOSFET, power diode, thyristor, and IGBT.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The power diode and power MOSFET operate on similar principles to their low-power counterparts, but are able to carry a larger amount of current and are typically able to withstand a larger reverse-bias voltage in the *off-state*.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Structural changes are often made in a power device in order to accommodate the higher current density, higher power dissipation, and/or higher reverse breakdown voltage.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The vast majority of the discrete (i.e., non-integrated) power devices are built using a vertical structure, whereas small-signal devices employ a lateral structure.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] With the vertical structure, the current rating of the device is proportional to its area, and the voltage blocking capability is achieved in the height of the die.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] With this structure, one of the connections of the device is located on the bottom of the semiconductor die.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The power MOSFET is the most common power device in the world, due to its low gate drive power, fast switching speed, and advanced paralleling capability.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] It has a wide range of power electronic applications, such as portable information appliances, power integrated circuits, cell phones, notebook computers, and the communications infrastructure that enables the Internet.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] As of 2010, the power MOSFET accounts for the majority (53%) of the power transistor market, followed by the IGBT (27%), then the RF amplifier (11%), and then the bipolar junction transistor (9%).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A majority carrier device is faster, but the charge injection of minority carrier devices allows for better on-state performance.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] In reality, the design of a diode is a trade-off between performance in on-state, off-state, and commutation.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] These trade-offs are the same for all power devices; for instance, a Schottky diode has excellent switching speed and on-state performance, but a high level of leakage current in the off-state.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] On the other hand, a PIN diode is commercially available in different commutation speeds (what are called "fast" and "ultrafast" rectifiers), but any increase in speed is necessarily associated with a lower performance in the on-state.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The trade-offs between voltage, current, and frequency ratings also exist for a switch.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] In fact, any power semiconductor relies on a PIN diode structure in order to sustain voltage; this can be seen in figure 2.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The power MOSFET has the advantages of a majority carrier device, so it can achieve a very high operating frequency, but it cannot be used with high voltages; as it is a physical limit, no improvement is expected in the design of a silicon MOSFET concerning its maximum voltage ratings.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] However, its excellent performance in low-voltage applications make it the device of choice (actually the only choice, currently) for applications with voltages below 200 V.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] By placing several devices in parallel, it is possible to increase the current rating of a switch.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The MOSFET is particularly suited to this configuration, because its positive thermal coefficient of resistance tends to result in a balance of current between the individual devices.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The IGBT is a recent component, so its performance improves regularly as technology evolves.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Basically, an IGBT is a bipolar transistor driven by a power MOSFET; it has the advantages of being a minority carrier device (good performance in the on-state, even for high-voltage devices), with the high input impedance of a MOSFET (it can be driven on or off with a very low amount of power).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The major limitation of the IGBT for low-voltage applications is the high voltage drop it exhibits in the on-state (2-to-4 V).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The net result is that the turn-off switching loss of an IGBT is considerably higher than its turn-on loss.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Generally, in datasheets, turn-off energy is mentioned as a measured parameter; that number has to be multiplied with the switching frequency of the intended application in order to estimate the turn-off loss.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] At very high power levels, a thyristor-based device (e.g., a SCR, a GTO, a MCT, etc.) is still often used.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] This device can be turned on by a pulse provided by a driving circuit, but cannot be turned off by removing the pulse.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A thyristor turns off as soon as no more current flows through it; this happens automatically in an alternating current system on each cycle, or requires a circuit with the means to divert current around the device.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Both MCTs and GTOs have been developed to overcome this limitation, and are widely used in electric power distribution applications.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A few applications of power semiconductors in switch mode include lamp dimmers, switched-mode power supplies, induction cookers, automotive ignition systems, and AC and DC electric motor drives of all sizes.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Amplifiers operate in the active region, where both device current and voltage are non-zero.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Consequently power is continually dissipated and its design is dominated by the need to remove excess heat from the semiconductor device.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Power amplifier devices can often be recognized by the heat sink used to mount the devices.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Multiple types of power semiconductor amplifier device exist, such as the bipolar junction transistor, the vertical MOS field effect transistor, and others.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Power levels for individual amplifier devices range up to hundreds of watts, and frequency limits range up to the lower microwave bands.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A complete audio power amplifier, with two channels and a power rating on the order of tens of watts, can be put into a small integrated circuit package, needing only a few external passive components to function.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Another important application for active-mode amplifiers is in linear regulated power supplies, when an amplifier device is used as a voltage regulator to maintain load voltage at a desired setting.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] While such a power supply may be less energy efficient than a switched-mode power supply, the simplicity of application makes them popular, especially in current ranges up to about one amp.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] **On-resistance**: Higher current ratings lower the on-resistances due to greater numbers of parallel cells.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] This increases overall capacitance and slows down the speed.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] **Rise and fall times**: The amount of time it takes to switch between the on-state and the off-state.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] **Safe-operating area**: This is a thermal dissipation and "latch-up" consideration.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] **Thermal resistance**: This is an often ignored but extremely important parameter from the point of view of practical designs; semiconductors do not perform well at elevated temperatures, when conducting large currents, power semiconductor devices invariably heat up.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Therefore, such devices, may usually need to be installed, so they will be cooled continuously; packaging and heatsink designs ... remove heat from semiconductor devices by conducting such to the external environment(s).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Generally, large current devices have large die and packaging surface areas and lower thermal resistances.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Many of the reliability issues of a power device are either related to excessive temperature or fatigue due to thermal cycling.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Research is also ongoing on electrical issues such as reducing the parasitic inductance of packaging; this inductance limits the operating frequency, because it generates losses during commutation.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A low-voltage MOSFET is also limited by the parasitic resistance of its package, as its intrinsic on-state resistance is as low as one or two milliohms.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Some of the most common type of power semiconductor packages include the TO-220, TO-247, TO-262, TO-3, D2Pak, etc.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The IGBT design is still under development and can be expected to provide increases in operating voltages.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] At the high-power end of the range, the MOS-controlled thyristor is a promising device.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] This is juxtaposed with a region that is similarly doped with the opposite carrier polarity (*holes*); these two similar, but oppositely doped regions effectively cancel out their mobile charge and develop a 'depleted region' that supports the high voltage during the off-state.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] On the other hand, during the on-state, the higher doping of the drift region allows for the easy flow of carriers, thereby reducing on-resistance.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Commercial devices, based on this super junction principle, have been developed by companies like Infineon (CoolMOS products) and International Rectifier (IR).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] The major breakthrough in power semiconductor devices is expected from the replacement of silicon by a wide band-gap semiconductor.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] At the moment, silicon carbide (SiC) is considered to be the most promising.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A SiC Schottky diode with a breakdown voltage of 1200 V is commercially available, as is a 1200 V JFET.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] As both are majority carrier devices, they can operate at high speed.
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] A bipolar device is being developed for higher voltages (up to 20 kV).
[src:igbt-power/power-semiconductor-device] Among its advantages, silicon carbide can operate at a higher temperature (up to 400 °C) and has a lower thermal resistance than silicon, allowing for better cooling.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] For power semiconductor devices (such as BJT, MOSFET, thyristor or IGBT), the **safe operating area** (SOA) is defined as the voltage and current conditions over which the device can be expected to operate without self-damage.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] SOA is usually presented in transistor datasheets as a graph with VCE (collector-emitter voltage) on the abscissa and ICE (collector-emitter current) on the ordinate; the safe 'area' referring to the area under the curve.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The SOA specification combines the various limitations of the device — maximum voltage, current, power, junction temperature, secondary breakdown — into one curve, allowing simplified design of protection circuitry.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Often, in addition to the continuous rating, separate SOA curves are also plotted for short duration pulse conditions (1 ms pulse, 10 ms pulse, etc.).
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The safe operating area curve is a graphical representation of the power handling capability of the device under various conditions.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The SOA curve takes into account the wire bond current carrying capability, transistor junction temperature, internal power dissipation and secondary breakdown limitations.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] SOA specifications are useful to the design engineer working on power circuits such as amplifiers and power supplies as they allow quick assessment of the limits of device performance, the design of appropriate protection circuitry, or selection of a more capable device.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] SOA curves are also important in the design of foldback circuits.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] In their early history, MOSFETs became known for their absence of secondary breakdown.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Recently, MOSFETs with very high transconductance, optimised for switching operation, have become available.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] When operated in linear mode, especially at high drain-source voltages and low drain currents, the gate-source voltage tends to be very close to the threshold voltage.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Unfortunately the threshold voltage decreases as temperature increases, so that if there are any slight temperature variations across the chip, then the hotter regions will tend to carry more current than the cooler regions when Vgs is very close to Vth.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] This can lead to thermal runaway and the destruction of the MOSFET even when it is operating within its Vds, Id and Pd ratings.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Some (usually expensive) MOSFETs are specified for operation in the linear region and include DC SOA diagrams, e.g.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Transistors require some time to turn off, due to effects such as minority carrier storage time and capacitance.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] While turning off, they may be damaged depending on how the load responds (especially with poorly snubbed inductive loads).
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The **reverse bias safe operating area** (or **RBSOA**) is the SOA during the brief time before turning the device into the off state—during the short time when the base current bias is reversed.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] As long as the collector voltage and collector current stay within the RBSOA during the entire turnoff, the transistor will be undamaged.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Typically the RBSOA will be specified for a variety of turn-off conditions, such as shorting the base to the emitter, but also faster turn-off protocols where the base-emitter voltage bias is reversed.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The RBSOA shows distinct dependencies compared to the normal SOA.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] For example in IGBTs the high-current, high-voltage corner of the RBSOA is cut out when the collector voltage increases too quickly.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Since the RBSOA is associated with a very brief turn-off process, it is not constrained by the continuous power dissipation limit.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The ordinary safe operating area (when the device is in the on state) may be referred to as the **Forward bias safe operating area** (or **FBSOA**) when it is possible to confuse it with the RBSOA.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The most common form of SOA protection used with bipolar junction transistors senses the collector-emitter current with a low-value series resistor.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] The voltage across this resistor is applied to a small auxiliary transistor that progressively 'steals' base current from the power device as it passes excess collector current.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] Another style of protection is to measure the temperature of the outside of the transistor, as an estimate of junction temperature, and reduce drive to the device or switch it off if the temperature is too high.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] If multiple transistors are used in parallel, only a few need to be monitored for case temperature to protect all parallel devices.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] This approach is effective but not bullet-proof.
[src:igbt-power/safe-operating-area] In practice, it is very difficult to design a protection circuit that will work under all conditions, and it is left up to the design engineer to weigh the likely fault conditions against the complexity and cost of the protection.
